    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Gracilaria verrucosa</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_7681",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Forms large, tangled masses of profusely and irregularly branching long, cylindrical fronds.&nbsp;Emerges from a small holdfast, but often found unattached or partially buried in sand. Colour straw to pale reddish-brown.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_7682",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Clumps up to 1 m long, blades only 1-2 mm wide.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_7683",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Temperate and tropical localities worldwide.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u><i> </i>Namibia to Swartkops Estuary in Eastern Cape.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_7684",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Very common in sheltered bays, lagoons and estuaries, where it forms large patches and often lies loose on the bottom, where it forms habitat for numerous small fish and invertebrates.</p><p>Washes up in large drifts after storms and has historically been collected and used for the extraction of agar, a gelling agent. Also has potential as a mariculture species and is cultivated on a large scale in China and Taiwan.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_7685",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_7686",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Mostly reproduce asexually by fragmentation and regrowth of the pieces. The sporophyte and gametophyte generation look similar.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_7687",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>A second species, <i>G. lemaneiformis </i>is almost indistinguishable, but occurs on sand-cover rocks along the open coast<i>.</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_7688",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Anderson, RJ, Stegenga, H & Bolton, JJ (2016). Seaweeds of the South African South Coast. World Wide Web electronic publication, University of Cape Town, http://southafrseaweeds.uct.ac.za; Accessed on 22 July 2024.<br><br>Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa (Fourth edition). Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 402). <br><br>Rebello, J, Ohno, M, Critchley, AT & Sawamura, M (1996). Growth rates and agar quality of <i>Gracilaria gracilis</i> (Stackhouse) Steentoft from Namibia, Southern Africa. <i>Botanica Marina</i>, 39, 273-279.<br><br>Stegenga, H, Bolton, J & Anderson, R (1997). Seaweeds of the South African west coast. <i>Contributions of the Bolus Herbarium</i>, 18. (p. 300 as <i>G. verrucosa</i>).",
